snippet.textDisplay:
I knew who Kobe was, but I just don't get to watch NBA in Australia. I totally would get into it though. It's probably the only non-martial arts sport I would get into watching on the screen.

But it's crazy, going over his stuff since his tragic death, you can just see how great of a person he is. I was still shocked when I heard the news and shared it online, but I think I followed him on a fine line and have avoided some pain that many of you reading this are going through.

I want to wish you all my condolences. I'm happy to see that he's left a powerful legacy which will live on to inspire so many of us.

snippet.textDisplay: I truly believe that when legends like Kobe leave our world, it proves that we are all connected.. because everyone feels that loss.. family, friends, fans, those he considered equals, enemies, even those who have no interest in basketball or even remotely cared about kobe.. it touches a chord in all of us, and shows that at the end of the day, we are truly all the same.. doesn't matter what color skin, religion...another important thing i took away when watching shaq talk about his relationship with Kobe, is that we should try to cleanse ourselves of any hate/grudges we may have against someone else, because there is a duality to this life that seems to hold the universe together.. in kobes case he defied the impossible with such a powerful career that most believed to be unattainable after what michael jordan did, but it was also these same unimaginable forces that have shocked the whole world by taking Kobe, Gianna, and the 7 friends of there's onboard in a split second.. just like when John Lennon died, a guy who brought so much joy and love to the world with his beautiful songs and lyrics, was also a victim of those same circumstances... killed by a self proclaimed loner who vied for the same love and attention john had received..
